Given that

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{y}&=3,\\
xy+x+y&=4,
\end{align*}

compute $x^2y+xy^2$.

Given that

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{y}&=3,\\
xy+x+y&=4,
\end{align*}

compute $x^2y+xy^2$.

response:
 Here, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{x}+\frac{1}{y}&=\frac{x+y}{xy}=3\\
xy+x+y&=4\end{align*}
Hence, $x+y=3xy$, so substituting this into the second equation gives $3xy(xy)+xy=4$. Factoring out $xy$, we see that $xy=1$, so $x+y=3$ by substitution. First, express $x^2y+xy^2$ as
\begin{align*}
x^2y+xy^2&=xy(x+y)\\
&=1\cdot 3\\
&=\boxed{\textbf{(C) } 3}.
\end{align*} </think> <answer> $\textbf{(C) }3$ </answer>

